From 1c158e897eccdc4e18a7893be5aa3aac7cee8605 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Sergio Andreozzi <digitalities@gmail.com>
Date: Sat, 18 Apr 2026 16:55:39 +0200
Subject: [PATCH] internet: Add TcpRetransmitTag packet tag stamped on
 retransmissions

Adds ns3::TcpRetransmitTag, a one-byte Tag subclass stamped by
TcpSocketBase::SendDataPacket when isRetransmission is true. The
three TCP retx paths (fast retransmit, RTO, SACK) all flow through
SendDataPacket, so a single stamp point catches them all.

DoForwardUp removes the tag at the receiver, alongside the
existing SocketPriorityTag strip, so the tag's lifetime is the
in-simulation path between sender SendDataPacket and receiver
DoForwardUp. Queue discs, AQM modules, and pcap tracers can read
it via Packet::PeekPacketTag.

This restores, as a minimal packet tag, the instrumentation that
ns-2 provided through hdr_tcp::reason_ (set by TcpAgent::output()
since the early 2000s, read by DiffServ queue discs to compute
per-class TCP goodput). ns-3 already classifies retransmissions
internally via TcpSocketBase::TcpPacketType_t::RE_XMT (added in
!2133 for RFC 3168 ECN compliance), but the classification was not
exposed to downstream queue discs; this MR adds that bridge.

Regression test tcp-retransmit-tag (internet/test/tcp-retransmit-tag-test.cc)
uses the TcpGeneralTest harness with a ReceiveListErrorModel that
drops one segment, forcing a fast retransmit. The sender-side Tx
trace checks for at least one tagged retransmission and a fresh-Tx
majority; the receiver-side Rx trace checks that no packet delivered
to the receiver socket still carries the tag.

